vectorData.altText:
Images: sagittal        , coronal        and axial        T1-weighted MRI
What does the time course of symptom onset suggest you should consider as the pathology underlying the symptoms? Is it more likely a tumour or a stroke?
Find the lesion on each of the image planes.
Describe the anatomical location of the lesion.
In the sagittal T1-weighted image without contrast, what do the areas of the lesion that are “dark” (low signal) represent? Hint: how does the fluid in the ventricles appear in these T1 images? 
Why do some parts of the lesion become bright with gadolinium?  List the possible causes for enhancement with contrast.
Estimate the location of primary motor cortex on the sagittal and coronal images. Based on both imaging and clinical presentation, what functional portion of the motor cortex is being affected by the tumour?
Explain the patient’s drooping right side of mouth and flattened right nasolabial fold. Why can he raise his right eyebrow?
